title: For Sale/Trade:  WTS/WTT: M85NP .223/5.56 AK converted to full rifle (uses AR-15 mags)
postcontent:
Letting this gun go. I really enjoy shooting it, but I am wanting something new, and prefer to keep my AR-15s

Gun started life as a Yugo M85NP AK pistol, 5.56x45, 10.5" chrome lined barrel. A 6.5" faux barrel extension was blind pinned (total length is 16.7" when measured from the bolt face to the end of the barrel extension). The rear trunnion was drilled and the gun was fitted with an ACE skeleton stock. A wedge kit was used, the rear trunnion is angled on these guns, so the wedge corrects the stock angle and gives a stronger mounting point for the stock than tapping the rear trunnion would. The entire gun was stripped and duracoated black, so everything is one uniform color. 

The handguard was replaced with a Manticore Arms renegade handguard and the grip was replaced with a Magpul AK grip, both are black. The only real downside of this gun (if you can even call it one) is that it MUST be used with US made magazines to remain 922R compliant. The handguard, stock and grip are 3 parts, and the magazine would be another 3, giving the 6 total required for an AK. It didn't bother me much as the gun has an AR-15 magazine adapter on it and I do not know of a single company that makes AR-15 mags outside of the US. I have run this gun with Pmags, Lancer mags, Troy mags, and normal C-Products metal mags. Have never had a single problem with any of them, other than pmags being a slightly tight fit in the magwell and not dropping free. My troy, lancer and metal mags all drop free from the gun. 

The gun currently has a stormwerkz top rail on the dust cover and is wearing a Bushnell TRS-25 on a short QD riser. I have not been to the range to zero the TRS-25 yet. It does not co-witness with or without the riser, so I added the short riser to allow quick removal and installation of the sight to switch to iron sights if wanted. The rail sits low enough on the dust cover that it does not interfere with sight picture using the iron sights. 

I am including two 30 round metal mags with the gun. No case, as I never got around to buying one for this gun, I typically would just put it in the factory plastic case that came with my Stag AR as it fit easily. 

I have a LOT of money into the gun, parts, gunsmithing and refinishing on this. I'm not expecting to get my money back out of it, just looking for an amount that is fair. 

Asking $850 for the gun without the optic/riser and $925 with the optic and riser. $1050 trade value.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Universal M1 Carbine
postcontent:
Full disclosure- the rifle needs some work. Luckily, it's amateur gunsmithing work at most.

The rear sight has had the actual aperture snapped off, meaning a new rear sight assembly will need to be dovetailed into the receiver.

The barrel band retainer spring on the stock has slipped out of place. This could be fixed by either buying a new stock set (this is an older-model carbine, pre-potbelly, so USGI stocks should work if I'm not mistaken), or by forcing the spring back into its proper place and wood caulking it shut which might look slightly ghetto but should work well enough.

Aside from that, the rifle doesn't have an oiler so you'd need one of those if you intended to sling it up, and the barrel band on the rifle lacks a bayonet lug- so if that's something that's important to you, you'd need to acquire and install a new one.


The rifle has an M2-style 30 round magazine and a standard full USGI-style stock set. She eats pretty much any ammunition I feed her, which is nice because .30 carbine is pretty uncommon unless you want to do bulk orders online.


Price point is based on gunbroker prices (less the cost of the parts the rifle will probably need, and less a bit due to some normal finish wear), and what my personal bottom dollar is. Feel free to email me with questions or whatever, I'm a pretty laid back guy and even if we don't end up doing business I'd be happy to explain what I know about the gun if you'd care to hear it.

Apologies for no photos, I'm not in a place where I can take fantastically good ones right now. I'll try and get a few soon.

I got this quite some time ago and built a slug gun to hunt on the military base where you can only use a shotgun. The slug barrel is ported to help manage recoil and has a built in cantilever scope mount so that you can remove the scope with the barrel and it will stay sighted in. the scope is a Simmons prodiamond 4x32 scope. I've also added a sling swivel to the slug barrel so it can be slinged. I shot lightfield sabot slugs through this gun and it is very capable of 150-200 yards. I dropped the gun accidentally a few years back and damaged the scope around the lens. title: For Sale:  Kahr P380 with Tritium Sights
postcontent:
Kahr P380 with Trijicon Night Sights 

Fantastic pocket pistol, this gun has had 250 rounds of ball ammo through it for break-in and 50 rounds of Hornady critical defense. I purchased this gun for my wife in December of 2013 (at the height of the gun craze for $800). Since she purse carries, the extremely small size isn't as important an issue for her. She now prefers to carry a slightly larger CCW. I have a P380 that I pocket carry, primarily use with shorts and a t-shirt in the summer time. Absolutely love it, so small, so compact. But, I don't need two. Here are the stats:

- Locked breach browning type action
- 4.9" overall legnth
- 3.9" height
- .75" wide
- 2.53" premium Match Grade polygonal rifled Lothar-Walther barrel.
- Forged Stainless steel slide.
- Polymer frame with integral stainless steel rails
- About 11 ounces in weight
- Dovetail Trijicon front & rear night sights
- Manual slide lock
- Striker fired
- Pachmayr slip-on grip sleeve
- (2) 6 round magazines

If you don't know the difference from the P380 and the CW380 let me inform you. The P series of Kahr pistols is their "premium" line and the CW series is the budget line. Some of the differences are:

- P380 has a match grade barrel, CW380 has a NON MATCH conventionally rifled barrel (I can tell you that this pistol is ridiculously accurate, way more accurate than I can be. Not that is means much, in a life/death situation, but I can easily put rounds on a steel silhouette target from 100 yards)
- The P380 has laser cut markings vs. the roll marks of the CW380
- The P380 has more refined contours compared to the more basic Slide machining contours of the CW380
- The P380 comes with premium front/rear trijicon night sights compared to the basic sights of the CW380
- The slide release, takedown lever, etc are Forged parts on the P380 compared to (MIM) metal injected mold parts on the CW380

$475.  Don't hesitate to text for additional pictures or questions. 8six5-3six8-2six52. Cash only, only trade I would entertain would be a Glock 42.
